# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-centura
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:chrysler-centura/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The **Borg-Warner 35 transmission** (BW-35) is an automatic transmission produced by the BorgWarner company.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] This article also applies to variations—the M-36 and M-37.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] When this article refers to "M-3x" it refers to all models.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] When model number specific it will use the exact model number.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The "3" in the number refers to the specific series of transmission.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The M-3x, 4x, 5x and 6x transmissions are all aluminum cased transmissions that are related to the M-35 (the first of the aluminum Borg-Warner automatics).
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] In this case the rising series number is relative to transmission strength—a larger number will withstand more power than a smaller number.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] This isn't, however, a general rule with Borg-Warner automatics.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The earlier M-8 and M-1x cast iron case transmissions are much stronger than the aluminum models, although the M-6x may handle as much power as the M-1x series.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The second number refers to a specific variation.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] This usually indicates a higher torque load capability, but may refer to other variations that may not increase torque rating.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The M-3x has three forward and one reverse gears.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The selector lever varies depending on years and car models the transmission is used in.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] All models follow a quadrant which has six stations.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] Early models have two drive positions marked with a "2" and a "1" (P-R-N-D2-D1-L; Park, Reverse, Neutral, D2, D1 and Lock).
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] These models start off in Second gear when in the D2 position.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] This is useful for economy in relatively flat terrain and for starting on slippery surfaces (wet mud, snow, ice, etc.).
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] When placed in the D1 position the transmission shifts through all three forward gears.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] In "Lock" the transmission can be locked to prevent upward gear changes and will provide maximum engine braking in 1st gear and moderate engine braking in 2nd gear.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] By selecting L from stationary, or before an upward gear change into 2nd gear, the transmission will become locked in 1st gear.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] By selecting L from D2 or D1 while in 2nd gear, the transmission will become locked in 2nd gear or from D2 or D1 when cruising below 55 m.p.h (88 k.p.h.) will effect an immediate downward change and lock in 2nd gear.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] In both these instances, the transmission will automatically change down into 1st gear when the car speed drops below 5 m.p.h.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] Should 1st gear be required earlier, reduce the car speed to below 30 m.p.h.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] (48 k.p.h.) and effect a "kick-down" gear change.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] Many people assume they have a two speed transmission because they expect the first Drive position (D2) to shift through all three gears as all automatic transmissions have done since 1968.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] Some vehicles had the same system without the D1 and D2, instead just having D, and only 5 stations on the quadrant.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] Starting in 1965 the M-3x was made with the now common P-R-N-D-2-1 shift arrangement (Park, Reverse, Neutral, Drive, Second gear, First gear).
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] AMC called this "Shift-Command" to differentiate it from the D2/D1 models, since either could be ordered in an AMC/Rambler automobile from 1965 to 1967.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] It is essentially the same as the M-35 except that it has provisions for an external transmission oil cooler.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The M-35 was air cooled by the torque converter with a fan on it.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The M-35 case has provisions to be drilled for an external cooler, but no U.S. models used an external cooler and do not have the internal provisions to mount one.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] There may be European models that were equipped with external coolers.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] An external oil cooler made it suitable for heavier vehicles and/or towing heavier loads.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] AMC used the M-36 behind the 232 six in their Ambassador starting in 1965.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The M-37 is first mentioned in the 1967 AMC Technical Service Manual (TSM).
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] It was used behind the 232 in larger vehicles.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] It has a higher torque rating than the M-35 and M-36.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] By 1967 the M-36 was relegated to the 199 six, the 232 received the stronger M-37 in all AMC vehicles.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The Borg Warner 35 automatic transmission comprises a torque converter, and a fully automatic 3-speed hydraulically controlled epicyclic gear box.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The automatic transmission provides three forward speeds, and one reverse gear ratio.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] As is common in automatic transmissions of its generation, power brought to the transmission via the torque converter drives hydraulic fluid.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] As the gears move faster or slower, pressure of the fluid increases or decreases in the case.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] Mechanical switching of gears is triggered by the increase or decrease of pressure.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] There are no electronic sensors or switches as found in modern transmissions.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] There is a Throttle Valve in the control valve body that is connected to the throttle linkage via a cable.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] This regulates internal pressure by throttle position.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] A secondary function of this cable is to down-shift ("kick down") to a lower gear when the Throttle Valve is in the full stop position (throttle pedal is fully depressed) and road speed is below a set point regulated by a mechanical governor on the output shaft.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The hydraulic control system consists of a valve arrangement and an engine driven pump.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The automatic transmission contains a planetary gear set consisting of two sun gears, two sets of three planet pinions contained within a planetary carrier and ring gear.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] Various speed ratios are obtained by holding or clutching various combinations of elements of the planetary train.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] This is performed by two bands, two multi-disc clutches and a one-way clutch.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] When the transmission of the motionless vehicle is placed in Drive, the transmission allows the vehicle to move off in first gear, then will change to second and then to third gear based on an increase in road speed.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The BW-35 will downshift from third to second and from second to first, also based on load.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The transmission is equipped to produce kickdown and will upshift after kickdown if accelerator pressure is released following a kickdown.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The Borg Warner 35 was designed for use with Type F Automatic Transmission Fluid (ATF), which is far less common today than the Mercon/Dexron type.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] Initially produced in the U.S. in the 1950s specifically for engines of less than 200 cubic inches engine displacement and less than 140 hp (100 kW) (American Motors Rambler and Studebaker mainly).
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] Prior and contemporary automatic transmissions were very inefficient and would work best with larger, more powerful engines, and even when used in those applications, the engines would often have higher compression ratios and more power than the manual transmission versions.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] Prior automatic transmissions were used with the small sixes in the US in the late 50s and early 60s, but the heavy internal components of the early automatics were detrimental to economy, the main reason a lighter automatic transmission was developed.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] In addition, lower differential ratios differentials were usually used in other automatic transmission applications to improve gas mileage (again due to the inefficiency of the earlier automatics, especially when used with small engines).
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The BW 35 was a more efficient transmission and was quite successful in the US with the smaller engined cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] This also made it a natural for European cars that usually had much smaller engines than American cars of that era.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] Production was transferred in 1960 to the Borg-Warner plant at Letchworth in Great Britain.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The BW-35 was offered to European automobile producers where it was widely used.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The BW-35 was also manufactured in Australia from 1963 and was used on numerous Australian made cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The 4.4l V8 engine may be the largest capacity engine ever fitted to a Model 35.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] Early automatic Ford Falcons used the two-speed **Fordomatic**, from 1960 to 1965.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The 4.1 litre Six (as an optional transmission) and 4.9 litre V8 used the Ford C4-3.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The 5.8 litre V8 came equipped with the Ford FMX-3, which was an evolved three-speed **Ford-O-Matic** (designed by Borg Warner Corporation), via the "MX" and "FX" (**Cruise-O-Matic**) transmissions to become the **FMX** in 1968.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] From 1967 to 1981, the Borg-Warner 35 transmission was also used in the 6-cylinder Australian Chryslers, Valiants, Chargers and Centuras.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The specification-change from the Torqueflite automatic transmission to the Borg-Warner 35 transmission was due to a requirement for more local content.
[src:chrysler-centura/borg-warner-35-transmission] The Borg-Warner 35 transmission was used behind the Hemi 6 engines.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Morse Equalizing Spring Company was the oldest forerunner, founded in 1880.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] BorgWarner Automotive Service Parts Division was also founded in the 1930s, and in 1936, the company commissioned a sterling silver trophy for the Indianapolis 500 (the Borg-Warner Trophy).
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 1937, Stieber Rollkupplung GmbH (the predecessor to BorgWarner GmbH) was founded in Munich in 1937.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In the prewar 1940s, BorgWarner created its Spring Division (to supply automatic transmission parts), began working on transfer cases, and soon directed its attention to World War II production needs.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 1950, it developed its first lock-up torque converter, a three-speed automatic transmission (the 'Ford-O-Matic'), along with Holley brand Borg & Beck Carburetors.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Studebaker and Ford initiated long-term cooperations in regard to the newly developed technologies.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] The company's automotive sales reached over $200 million at the time.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] As the 1950s continued, BorgWarner expanded its operations, establishing Borg & Beck do Brasil South America and setting up new facilities in Simcoe, Ontario, and Letchworth (England).
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 1957, the T-10 4-speed transmission was introduced initially as a Corvette exclusive, it was soon used by all major American automakers through the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] The English facility was soon producing Warner Gear's overdrive units and the Model D.G. automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Marvel-Schebler was developing fuel injection systems, while BorgWarner developed a line of paper-related wet friction components.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Later on, BorgWarner acquired Coote & Jurgenson, an Australian transmission producer for cars and tractors in 1957.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Three years later, Brummer Seal Company was merged into BorgWarner's Spring Division.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 1962, BorgWarner expanded into Mexico, and into Asia with two Japanese joint ventures (NSK-Warner and Tsubakimoto-Morse).
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 1969, Aisin-Warner was formed as another joint venture in Japan to build automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] The following year, BorgWarner acquired the Massachusetts-based Nu-Era Gear and developed the Model 45 automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Marvel-Schebler expanded by merging with Tillotson Carburetor in 1971.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 1973, BorgWarner introduced its full-time, four-wheel drive (4WD) transfer cases, while a new manufacturing site opened in Ireland.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Over the next several years, came the introduction of the Model T-50 five-speed transmission and continuously variable transmissions for commercial vehicles.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Further, expansion took place with new plants in Arkansas and New York.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] BorgWarner also diversified into several other industries, while its automotive division remained contributing upwards of 50 percent of BorgWarner's total revenue.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 1979, BorgWarner's overall sales topped $2.7 billion.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] This was due in part to its continuing improvement of the T-4 and T-5 manual transmissions and its production of new, lightweight Transfer cases.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] BorgWarner also restructured itself by selling Morse Industrial and its automotive service parts divisions in 1981.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Three years later, the company consolidated its automotive operations under the umbrella of the Borg-Warner Automotive Inc.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Sales for the newly named automotive conglomerate topped $1 billion in 1984 and the company employed around 10,000 people.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] It also produced its one-millionth T-5 manual transmission that year, while continuing its consolidation.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] During this time, Warner Gear was renamed Transmission Systems, Borg & Beck was renamed Clutch Systems, and Marvel-Schebler became known as Control Systems.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Additionally, the company opened sales offices in Frankfurt, São Paulo, Seoul, and Tokyo and signed a licensing agreement with Nanjing Motor Works of Beijing.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Following the consolidation, in 1987, Borg-Warner Corporation ceased to exist as a result of a series of complex financial transactions involving Merrill Lynch & Co., although a new company of the same name (still BorgWarner Corporation) continued the business.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] At the same time, Borg-Warner Automotive Inc. became a subsidiary of the new mother company, Borg-Warner Corporation, later known as Borg-Warner Security Corporation.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Around 1990, BorgWarner's transfer case technology was introduced for heavy duty and all-wheel drive models from General Motors.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] The company also developed the new 1354 transmission model for Ford Explorers and Ranger trucks, while the 'touch drive' model was installed in all F-series trucks.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In the early 1990s, Ford signed another sole-source agreement for the rest of the decade.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Meanwhile, the T-56 six-speed manual transmission became standard in Chrysler's Viper sportscar and new Ford Mustangs, and international operations were expanded in Japan and China.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 1993, Borg-Warner Automotive Inc. was spun-off from Borg-Warner Security Corporation and became an independent company.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In June 1996, BorgWarner acquired three automotive operations (Holley Automotive, Coltec Automotive, and Performance Friction Products) from Coltec Industries Inc.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] The acquired businesses were manufacturers of a range of products, including air induction systems, throttle bodies, electric air pumps, and oil pumps.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In December 1996, BorgWarner sold its North American manual transmission business to Mexico-based Transmisiones y Equipos Mecanicos S.A. de C.V.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 1998, BorgWarner entered the market segment of turbochargers, through the acquisition of Kühnle, Kopp & Kausch AG, a German maker of turbochargers and turbomachinery.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Later on, the company was renamed to 3K-Warner Turbosystems GmbH.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In March 1999, BorgWarner increased its operations in the turbocharger business with the purchase of Kuhlman Corporation.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Kuhlman consisted of three main businesses, two of which were sold off later in 1999.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] The third unit was Schwitzer, Inc., a maker of heavy-duty steel fuel tanks, fan drives, and turbochargers for diesel engines, which was later on incorporated in 3K-Warner.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 2005, BorgWarner's world headquarters was moved from Chicago to the metro Detroit area.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Further, between 2006 and 2014, the organization invested in new production facilities, including in South Korea, France, Germany, China, Hungary, Poland, India, Brazil, Portugal, Mexico and Thailand.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] It also acquired several other companies.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] This included the 2005 takeover of a majority stake in Beru AG (named after the founders Behr & Ruprecht), a supplier of diesel cold-start technology, sensors, electronics and ignition technology based in Ludwigsburg, Germany.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] This was followed by the acquisition of Sweden-based Haldex Traction Systems, known for the *Haldex clutch*, a multi-plate wet clutch used in four-wheel-drive passenger cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 2014, BorgWarner took over German-based Gustav Wahler GmbH & Co.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] KG, a manufacturer of exhaust gas recirculation valves and pipes as well as coolant control valves, and in 2015, Remy International, Inc., a producer of rotating electrical components, combining it with TorqTransfer Systems and renaming the company to PowerDrive Systems.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 2017, BorgWarner took over UK-based Sevcon Inc., which produces microprocessor controls for electric vehicles.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Further, the company invested in Autotech Ventures, a venture capital fund, to gain access to startups involved in ground transportation.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] This was followed by a cooperation with Plug and Play as well as Franklin Venture Partners in 2018, representing the second and third Silicon Valley initiative for BorgWarner in the field of mobility and propulsion technologies.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Subsequently, in 2019, BorgWarner acquired Rinehart Motion Systems, AM Racing, as well as set up the joint venture Romeo Systems, Inc., expanding existing activities in electric vehicle applications.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] With the acquisition of Delphi Technologies in 2020, BorgWarner expanded its operations in the field of power electronics, software and calibration capabilities, as well as other products.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 2021, the company acquired five additional companies in the field of electric vehicle services.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] This included German-based battery manufacturer Akasol in the same year and in 2022, Santroll Automotive Components and Rhombus Energy Solutions.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In December 2022, BorgWarner had acquired the Swiss-based company Drivetek AG, a manufacturer of engineering and products for inverters, electric components, and power electronics.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In July 2023, BorgWarner spun off its fuel parts and aftermarket segments as part of a plan to focus on its electric vehicle drivetrain business.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] The newly created standalone company PHINIA, which took over the fuel parts and aftermarket segments, publicly trades on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] BorgWarner Inc., together with its subsidiaries, is a Delaware corporation incorporated in 1987.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] The company operates manufacturing facilities in Europe, the Americas and Asia and is an original equipment supplier to most major automotive OEM in the world.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 2022, BorgWarner employed around 52,000 people and generated revenues of US$15.8 billion.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Frédéric Lissalde has been CEO of BorgWarner Inc. since August 1, 2018.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Since the spin-off of its fuel parts and aftermarket segments in 2023 as part of a plan to focus on its electric vehicle drivetrain business, BorgWarner has been operating in the following business segments: air management, e-propulsion and drivetrain.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] The company develops and manufactures products for conventional gas, hybrid and electric vehicles.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] BorgWarner has also been supplying its products to tier-one vehicle systems suppliers.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] BorgWarner has close links with the Indianapolis 500.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In the NTT IndyCar Series, BorgWarner's EFR (Engineered for Racing) turbocharger has been fitted in all participating vehicles in each season since 2012.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] Since 1936, the company has also appeared as the sponsor of the Borg-Warner Trophy, which serves as an annual prize for the winner of the Indianapolis 500.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] In 2017, BorgWarner became an international partner of SOS Children's Villages.
[src:chrysler-centura/borgwarner] This entails flagship projects around the world each year, in which both the company's management and selected employees participate.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] There are many types of car body styles.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] They vary depending on intended use, market position, location, and the era they were made.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Lightweight off-road vehicle with sparse bodywork.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Originally two- or four-wheeled carriages in the 19th and early 20th centuries pulled by one horse, the motorized buggies were developed in the 1960s and grew in popularity and diversity.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] A convertible allows an open-air driving experience, with the ability to provide a roof when required.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Most convertible roofs are either a folding textile soft-top or a retractable metal roof.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Convertibles with a metal roof are sometimes called 'retractable hardtop', 'coupé convertible', or 'coupé cabriolet'.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Two-door car, seating up to four persons.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Some two-door cars have only two seats, thus **two-seaters**.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Type of SUV with a sloping roofline similar to fastback cars, That is often adopted to offer a styling advantage compared to standard SUVs.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Manufacturers often sell them as more premium models than their standard SUV counterparts.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Vehicle with a higher ground clearence and larger space, That is built in a unibody platform shared with standard cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Originally a North American term used for vehicles that blend characteristics between two types, it evolved to be a term for SUVs built in a unibody chassis, Even though the term SUV is used to refer both to crossovers and standard SUVs due to their visual similarities.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Car with a roofline that slopes continuously down at the back.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] The design features a single unbroken convex curve from the roof to the rear.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Used in the U.S. in the funeral industry to carry flowers for burial services.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Typically a coupé-style, forward-passenger compartment with an open well in the rear.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Car with a hatch-type rear door that is hinged at the roof and opens upwards.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] The term "hatchback" can also refer to that type of rear door, which is also used on several sports cars, SUVs, and large luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] The modification of a passenger car to provide a long cargo area for carrying a coffin or casket.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Hearses often have large glass panels for viewing the coffin.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] A vehicle that combines characteristics and styling of a sedan with a higher ground clearance, Similar to a crossover.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] A Kammback is a car where the rear slopes downwards before being abruptly cut off with a vertical or near vertical surface.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] This reduces the aerodynamic drag, improving the efficiency, while the stil keeping its traditional shape.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Variant of a hatchback where the roof line and the rear cargo door are more horizontal than vertical.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] A luxury-type vehicle that is typically driven by a chauffeur with a partition between the driver's compartment and the passenger's compartment.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Limousines may also be stretched to provide more room in the rear passenger compartment.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] In some European usage, the word describes a regular four-door sedan body style.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Vehicle designed to transport passengers in the rear seating row(s) with reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Typically has a combined passenger and cargo area, a high roof, a flat floor, a sliding door for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] In Europe, some small minivans have been marketed as 'leisure activity vehicles'.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Car with a distinct rear section, With the back of the passenger compartment being in an angle to the top of what is generally the baggage compartment.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] A cargo vehicle based upon passenger car chassis and typically has one row of seats with no side windows at the rear.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] A panel van is smaller than a panel truck or cargo van and is often built on a car platform.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] A panel truck is a larger version of the panel van and is often built on a heavier platform.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] In South Africa, a pickup truck is called a "bakkie".
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] An open two-seat car with emphasis on sporting appearance or character.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Initially, an American term for a two-seat car with no weather protection, usage has spread internationally and has evolved to include two-seat convertibles.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] These form separate compartments for engine, passenger, and cargo.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] A sedan is called a "berlina" in Spanish and Italian, or a "berline" in French.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Initially, a horse-drawn vehicle used to carry shooting parties with their equipment and game; subsequently synonymous with station wagon / estate car; and in contemporary usage a three- or five-door wagon combining features of a station wagon and a coupé.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Type of vehicle that combines characteristics of a passenger car with a offroad vehicle, like higher ground clearence and four wheel drive.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Has a two-box design, a large cargo area, and a rear tailgate that is hinged to open for access to the cargo area.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] The body style is similar to a hatchback car; however, station wagons are longer and are more likely to have the roofline extended to the rear of the car (resulting in a vertical rear surface to the car) to maximize the cargo space.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] In French, a station wagon is called a "break".
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] A semi-convertible style used on some sports cars, featuring a fully removable soft or hard roof panel that leaves the A and B pillars in place on the car body.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Based on a passenger sedan chassis and has a cargo tray in the rear integrated with the passenger body (as opposed to a pickup truck, which has a separate cargo tray).
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] In Australia, the term "ute" was originally used solely for coupé utility cars; however, in recent years, it has also been used for pickup trucks.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Has two rows of raised seats, similar to horse-drawn carriages; usually did not have front doors, a roof, or a windshield.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] The baquet ("bathtub") style was produced in the early 1900s in Europe.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Also a marketing term used on cars built in the United States in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Italian two-seat sports car with either an open-top or convertible roof.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] The term was originally used for lightweight open-top racing cars from the late 1940s through the 1950s.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Since the 1950s, the name barchetta ("little boat" in Italian) has been revived on several occasions, mostly for cars with convertible roofs that are not specifically intended for racing.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Italian sports coupé, typically with two seats but also including 2+2 cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] A retractable textile roof, similar to a convertible/cabriolet.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] The difference is that where a convertible often has the B-pillar, C-pillar, and other bodywork removed, the cabrio-coach retains all bodywork to the top of the door frames and just replaces the roof skin with a retractable fabric panel.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Some modern cars, Like the Fiat 500 (2007), featured this body style.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] An external or open-topped driver's position and an enclosed compartment for passengers.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Although the different terms may have once had specific meanings for certain car manufacturers or countries, the terms are often used interchangeably.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Some coupé de villes have the passengers separated from the driver in a fully enclosed compartment, while others have a canopy for the passengers and no partition between the driver and the passengers (therefore passengers enter the compartment via the driver's area).
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Usually describes pillarless hardtops that are cars without a B-pillar often styled to give the appearance of a convertible.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Popular in the United States from the mid 1950s through the mid 1970s.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] It also refers to a separate top that is removable and made of metal or other hard material for sports cars or small SUVs.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] A car where the rear passengers are covered by a convertible top.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Often the driver is separated from the rear passengers with a partition, as per a limousine.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] American luxury coupés and convertibles produced from 1952 to 2007.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] The cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] An open-roof automobile without any fixed weather protection, which was popular from the 1900s until the 1930s.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] An open-topped roadster body and a rear cargo bed.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] A light, inexpensive, open car with basic bodywork and no windshield, top, or doors.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Most runabouts had just a single row of seats, providing seating for two passengers.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] Body style was a type of automobile body used from 1908 until the mid-1930s, which had a streamlined profile and a folding or detachable soft top.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] The design consists of a hood or bonnet line raised to be level with the car's waistline, resulting in a straight beltline from front to back.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] A style of open car built in the United States that seats four or more people.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-body-style] The style was popular from the early 1900s to the 1930s.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Governments and private organizations have developed **car classification** schemes that are used for various purposes including regulation, description, and categorization of cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The International Standard ISO 3833-1977 *Road vehicles – Types – Terms and definitions* also defines terms for classifying cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The following table summarises the commonly used terms of market segments and legal classifications.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Microcars and their Japanese equivalent— kei cars— are the smallest category of automobile.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Microcars straddle the boundary between car and motorbike, and are often covered by separate regulations from normal cars, resulting in relaxed requirements for registration and licensing.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Engine size is often 700 cc (43 cu in) or less, and microcars have three or four wheels.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Microcars are most popular in Europe, where they originated following World War II.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The predecessors to micro cars are voiturettes and cycle cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Kei cars have been used in Japan since 1949.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The smallest category of vehicles that are registered as normal cars is called A-segment in Europe, or "city car" in Europe and the United States.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The United States Environmental Protection Agency defines this category as "minicompact." However, this term is not widely used.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The equivalents of A-segment cars have been produced since the early 1920s.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] However, the category increased in popularity in the late 1950s when the original Fiat 500 and BMC Mini were released.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The next larger category of small cars is called B-segment in Europe, supermini in the United Kingdom and subcompact in the United States.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The size of a subcompact car is defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), as having a combined interior and cargo volume of between 85–99 cubic feet (2,410–2,800 L).
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Since the EPA's smaller minicompact category is not as commonly used by the general public, A-segment cars are sometimes called subcompacts in the United States.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] In Europe and Great Britain, the B-segment and supermini categories do not have any formal definitions based on size.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Early supermini cars in Great Britain include the 1977 Ford Fiesta and Vauxhall Chevette.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] In the United States, the first locally-built subcompact cars were the 1970 AMC Gremlin, Chevrolet Vega, and Ford Pinto.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The largest category of small cars is called *C-segment* or *small family car* in Europe, and *compact car* in the United States.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The size of a compact car is defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), as having a combined interior and cargo volume of 100–109 cu ft (2.8–3.1 m3).
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] In Europe, the third-largest category for passenger cars is called *D-segment* or *large family car*.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] In the United States, the equivalent term is *mid-size* or *intermediate* cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) defines a mid-size car as having a combined passenger and cargo volume of 110–119 cu ft (3.1–3.4 m3).
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] In Europe, the second-largest category for passenger cars is E-segment / executive car, which are usually luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] In other countries, the equivalent terms are *full-size car* or *large car*, which are also used for relatively affordable large cars that are not considered luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Minivan is an American car classification for vehicles that are designed to transport passengers in the rear seating rows, and have reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The equivalent terms in British English are multi-purpose vehicle (MPV), people carrier, and people mover.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Minivans are often of the "one-box" or "two-box" body configuration, high roofs, flat floors, sliding doors for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Mini MPV is the smallest size of MPVs and the vehicles are often built on the platforms of B-segment hatchback models.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The compact MPV size class includes vehicles between the mini MPV and large MPV (minivan) sizes.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Compact MPVs remain predominantly a European phenomenon, although they are also built and sold in many Latin American and Asian markets.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The largest size of minivans is also referred to as "large MPV" and became popular following the introduction of the 1984 Renault Espace and Dodge Caravan.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Since the 1990s, the smaller compact MPV and mini MPV sizes of minivans have also become popular.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] If the term "minivan" is used without specifying a size, it usually refers to a large MPV.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The premium compact class (also called subcompact executive) is the smallest category of luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] It became popular in the mid-2000s, when European manufacturers — such as Audi, BMW, and Mercedes-Benz — introduced new entry-level models that were smaller and cheaper than their compact executive models.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] A compact executive car or a compact luxury car is a premium car larger than a *premium compact* and smaller than an *executive car*.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Compact executive cars are equivalent size to mid-size cars and are part of the D-segment in the European car classification.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] In North American terms, close equivalents are "luxury compact" and "entry-level luxury car", although the latter is also used for the smaller *premium compact cars*.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] An executive car is a premium car larger than a *compact executive* and smaller than a *full-size luxury* car.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Executive cars are classified as E-segment cars in the European car classification.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] In the United States and several other countries, the equivalent categories are full-size car (not to be confused with the European category of "full-size luxury car") or *mid-size luxury* car.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The largest size of a luxury car is known as a *luxury saloon* in the United Kingdom and a *full-size luxury car* in the United States.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] These cars are classified as F-segment cars in the European car classification.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Vehicles in this category are often the flagship models of luxury car brands.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Cars that prioritize handling or straight-line acceleration are called sports cars or performance cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] However the term "sports car" is also sometimes used specifically for lightweight two-seat cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Sports/performance cars can either be built on unique platforms or upgraded versions of regular cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The definitions for these categories are often blurred and a car may be a member of multiple categories.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Sports cars are designed to emphasize handling, performance, or the thrill of driving.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Sports cars originated in Europe in the early 1900s, with one of the first recorded usages of the term "sports car" being in *The Times* newspaper in the United Kingdom in 1919.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Sports cars started to become popular during the 1920s.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The term was originally used for two-seat roadsters (cars without fixed roofs).
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] However, since the 1970s the term has also been used for cars with fixed roofs (which were previously considered grand tourers).
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] A *sports sedan* — also known as "sports saloon" — is a subjective term for a sedan/saloon car that is designed to have sporting performance or handling characteristics.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] A supercar – also called an exotic car – is a loosely defined description of certain high-performance sportscars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Since the 1990s or 2000s, the term "hypercar" has come into use for the highest-performing supercars.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Passenger vehicles with off-road capability or styling features are often categorized as either off-road vehicles, sports utility vehicles, or crossover SUVs.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] There are no commonly agreed boundaries between these categories, and usage of the terms varies between countries.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The earliest type of passenger vehicle is called an "off-roader", "four-by-four" or "four-wheel drive".
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Off-road vehicles are usually more focused on off-road capability than SUVs and crossover SUVs (often compromising their on-road ride quality or handling).
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Common features of off-road vehicles are four-wheel drive, high ground clearance, a body-on-frame (separate chassis) construction and low-range gearing.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] A sports utility vehicle (SUV) combines elements of road-going passenger vehicles with features from off-road vehicles, such as raised ground clearance and four-wheel drive.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] There is no common definition of an SUV, and usage varies between countries.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Some definitions claim that an SUV must be built on a light-truck chassis.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] However, a broader definition considers any vehicle with off-road design features as an SUV.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] In some countries — such as the United States — SUVs have been classified as "light trucks", resulting in more lenient regulations compared to passenger vehicles.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The predecessors to SUVs date back to military and low-volume models from the late 1930s, and the four-wheel drive station wagons / carryalls that began to be introduced in 1949.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The 1984 Jeep Cherokee (XJ) is considered to be the first SUV in the modern style.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Most SUVs produced today use unibody construction (as per passenger cars).
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] However, in the past, many SUVs used body-on-frame construction.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] A crossover SUV— also called a crossover or CUV— is a type of sports utility vehicle (SUV) that uses a unibody construction.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Crossovers are often based on a platform shared with a passenger car, as a result, they typically have better comfort and fuel economy, but less off-road capability (many crossovers are sold without all-wheel drive) than truck-based SUVs, though more so than passenger four wheels.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] There are various inconsistencies about whether vehicles are considered crossovers or SUVs, therefore the term SUV is often used as a catch-all for both crossovers and SUVs.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] These classifications can be based on body style (e.g. sedan, coupe or hatchback), number of doors or seating capacity.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Government departments often create classification systems for taxation or regulating vehicle usage (e.g. vehicles that require a specific license or are restricted to certain roads).
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Some jurisdictions may determine vehicle tax based upon environmental principles, such as the user pays principle.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] In Australia, the Federal Chamber of Automotive Industries publishes its classifications.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] A similar set of classes is used by the Canadian EPA.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The classification of a three-box vehicle (sedan) is determined by its length, while the classification of a two-box car (hatchback and SUV) or MPV is determined by its wheelbase.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] In the United Kingdom, a vehicle is taxed according to the vehicle's construction, engine, weight, type of fuel, and emissions, as well as the purpose for which it is used.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] In the United States, since 2010 the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety has used a formula it developed that takes into account a combination of both vehicle footprint (length times width) and weight.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The United States National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) separates vehicles into classes by the curb weight of the vehicle with standard equipment including the maximum capacity of fuel, oil, coolant, and air conditioning, if so equipped.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The United States Federal Highway Administration has developed a classification system used for automatically calculating road use tolls.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] There are two broad categories depending on whether the vehicle carries passengers or commodities.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Vehicles that carry commodities are further subdivided by the number of axles and number of units, including both power and trailer units.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The United States Environmental Protection Agency (US EPA) has developed a classification system used to compare fuel economy among similar vehicles.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Passenger vehicles are classified based on a vehicle's total interior passenger and cargo volumes.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Trucks are classified based on their gross vehicle weight rating (GVWR).
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Heavy-duty vehicles are not included in the EPA scheme.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Certain cities in the United States in the 1920s chose to exempt electric-powered vehicles because officials believed those vehicles did not cause "substantial wear upon the pavements".
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Several other segment descriptions, listed below, are used in North America.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Cars from these segments may also be sold in other countries.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] However, the usage of the terms is mostly specific to North America.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Muscle car is an American term for high-performance cars, usually rear-wheel drive and fitted with a large and powerful V8 engine.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The term originated for the 1960s and early 1970s special editions of mass-production cars which were designed for drag racing.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Pony car is an American class of automobile launched and inspired by the Ford Mustang in 1964.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] It broke all post-World War II automobile sales records, "creating the 'pony car' craze soon adopted by competitors." The term describes an affordable, compact, highly styled car with a sporty or performance-oriented image.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] A personal luxury car is a North American market segment for premium coupé or convertible produced from 1952–2007.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] These two-door cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Not prioritizing maximum interior space, interior volumes are equivalent size to mid-size cars and are part of the D-segment in the European car classification, and exterior dimensions can exceed F-segment.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] A sporting version of an affordable compact car or a subcompact car.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] There is no precise definition and the description is applied for marketing purposes to a wide variety of models.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Cars began to be marketed as sport compacts in the mid-1980s when it was used for option packages on American-built coupes.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Since then, it has also been used for standalone sports car models and cars imported from Europe and Asia.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] However, sport compacts are not restricted to just hatchback body styles.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Several other segment descriptions, listed below, are used in Europe.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] However, the usage of the terms is mostly specific to Europe.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] A grand tourer (GT) is a car that is designed for high-speed and long-distance driving, due to a combination of performance and luxury attributes.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The most common format is a front-engine, rear-wheel-drive two-door coupé with either a two-seat or a 2+2 arrangement.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] The term derives from the Italian language phrase *gran turismo* which became popular in the English language from the 1950s, evolving from fast touring cars and streamlined closed sports cars during the 1930s.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Hot hatch (shortened from hot hatchback) is a high-performance version of a mass-produced hatchback car.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] However, factory high-performance versions of hatchbacks have been produced since the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Front-mounted petrol engines, together with front-wheel drive, are the most common powertrain layout.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] However, all-wheel drive has become more commonly used since around 2010.
[src:chrysler-centura/car-classification] Most hot hatches are manufactured in Europe or Asia.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The **Chrysler 180** was the base name for a series of large saloon cars produced by Chrysler Europe.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Resulting from joining the development efforts of Rootes Group and Simca, the car was produced from 1970 to 1975 in Poissy, France, and later in Chrysler's subsidiary Barreiros' factory in Spain.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The Chrysler 180 was also the base for the medium-sized model built by Chrysler Australia, the Chrysler Centura.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Depending on the engine, the cars were marketed as **Chrysler 160/180/2 litre**, and since 1977 in France and rest of continental Europe as **Chrysler-Simca 1609/1610/2 litres**.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] After the takeover of Chrysler Europe by PSA Peugeot Citroën, the continental Europe models were renamed **Talbot 1610/2 litres** for 1979 and 1980 model years, after which the model was discontinued in Europe with the exception of Spain, where a diesel model was sold until 1982.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The large, American-inspired Chrysler fared quite poorly in the principal European markets.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The replacement for the car was developed by Chrysler Europe under the codename *C9* and was finally launched by PSA as the even more ill-fated Talbot Tagora.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Although Chrysler gradually took financial control of both Simca and Rootes Group during the 1960s, there was little effort to coordinate the operations of both automakers.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Therefore, the first common European Chrysler car was actually a result of two separate development programs.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The plan was to market the car under three brands - the base version as Hillman, a 2.0-litre as Sunbeam 2000, and atop the range a Humber Hawk.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] A further development of the C Car with a stretched platform was planned, a "*D Car*", which was to replace the Humber Super Snipe.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The Rootes development program also comprised the development of a brand-new V6 engine of 2.0 and 2.5 litres, with a 60° vee angle.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Other design propositions included the use of De Dion tubes for rear suspension (like in the competing Rover P6), as well as a five-speed gearbox (which would still be an advanced feature at that time).
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] One of the engineers who worked on the design of the C Car was Tony Wheeler, who was later the founder of the Lonely Planet travel guides.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] At the same time, in France, Simca was working on ***Projet 929***, which would be Simca's first large car since the Vedette was discontinued in 1961, and also partially replace the Simca 1501 in its role of the range-topping Simca.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The car would not use a V6 engine, as the displacement-based *puissance fiscale* tax system in France would make the costs prohibitive, but rather four-cylinder units of more modest specifications.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] There were three styling propositions prepared for the new car.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The *929 XA* was styled by Simca's design team, featuring angular design and rather top-heavy proportions.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Bertone designed the *929 XB*, which was much more rounded and somewhat reminiscent of contemporary BMWs.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Finally, the *929 XC* was sent from Chrysler's Detroit design studios, and was very American in style, resembling a smaller version of what then became the Australian VE Series Chrysler Valiant.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] In early 1969, Chrysler realized that there were two potentially competing cars being developed and called for both the British and the French proposition to be presented before the general management of Chrysler Europe.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The decision was taken to go ahead with the British C Car program, but to develop two versions for both the UK and the French part of the concern.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Chrysler funded a new plant along with a development centre for the Rootes Group at the Whitley plant, Coventry, where the development was continued.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Roy Axe employed former Chrysler USA designer Curt Gwinn as project designer, and the C Car took a shape very similar to an enlarged version of the Hillman Avenger.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Initial designs were inspired by contemporary American Chryslers, with twin headlamps and a light bar in the rear.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] In 1970, however, Chrysler reviewed the programme once again and decided to trim it down to just one version, to be built in Simca's Poissy factory in France for all markets.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The V6 engine development was scrapped, despite the tooling for the new engine had been already installed in the Rootes' Humber Road factory.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The production cars also received a more conventional coil sprung rear live axle and MacPherson struts in the front and a four-speed manual transmission (with an option of a three-speed automatic).
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Following the renaming of Simca as "Chrysler France" and Rootes Group as "Chrysler UK" (which combined formed Chrysler Europe), the new large car was the first one to spearhead the concept of unifying the offerings from both sides of the Channel under the common brand.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Thus, the vehicle was launched as Chrysler 160, **160 GT** and 180.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] In a fashion similar to Simca models, the designations referred to the displacement of the engines employed by the given version.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The 160 featured the 1632 cc unit, while the 180 came with the 1812 cc one.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] However, the 160 GT model came equipped with the larger engine.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The three models were introduced in 1970 under the slogan " An American from Paris".
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The British launch took place in 1971, with only the 180 available.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The 2.0 L model (marketed as "Chrysler 2 litre") joined the lineup for 1973, unveiled at the Amsterdam Auto Show in February that year.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The 160 and 180 also gained some chrome and metal trim on the outside in 1972, and following the introduction of the 2.0-litre, all models featured 14-inch (rather than the previous 13-inch) road wheels and new hubcaps.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The 160 GT was discontinued at the same time.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] A Chrysler 180 saloon was tested by the British *Motor* magazine in April 1971, a few months after the model's UK launch.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] An overall fuel consumption of 21.7 miles per imperial gallon (13.0 L/100 km; 18.1 mpg‑US) was recorded.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The tested car was ranked third out of five UK market competitor vehicles: competitors identified by the magazine, behind the Ford Cortina Mk III 2000 GXL and the Vauxhall VX 4/90.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The overall tone of the road test, written at a time when new models were generally greeted with uncritical enthusiasm by UK motoring journalists, is summed up in its description of the Chrysler 180 as a "very pleasing car that only just falls short of being a luxury sporting saloon".
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Chrysler decided to move the assembly lines from the Poissy factory to the Villaverde plant of its Spanish subsidiary, Barreiros.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Barreiros had been assembling many Simca and Chrysler models previously for the protected Spanish market, but for the first time, it would become the sole supplier of the entire model line for all markets.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The vehicle became popular in its new home market, and local coachbuilders even created estate and stretched versions of the car.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The lineup remained mostly unchanged in most markets, although the 160 was not offered in Spain, which in turn received a new diesel model, powered by the Barreiros 2.0 L diesel engine (not offered in other European markets).
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The four-cylinder diesel featured with indirect injection.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] It was mated to the four-speed manual transmission and delivered 48 kilowatts (65 hp).
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The diesel model came with the most basic 160 dashboard.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] A change to the Spanish lineup was forced by the November 1978 introduction of the Spanish taxation system, similar to France's *puissance fiscale*.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The new *13 CV* tax band imposed a rate of 35% and encompassed both the petroleum and diesel 2.0 L models.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] While the petroleum 2.0 Litre model was replaced by a 180 automatic version, the diesel engine had to be modified for 1978 to avoid increased taxation.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The displacement was decreased from 2007 cc to 1917 cc (without a drop in actual maximum power or speed), just below the border of the *13 CV* tax band, which stood at 1920 cc.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] In 1977, the car was for the first time officially badged as Chrysler-Simca in continental Europe (the Simca badge appeared on the bootlid, while the stylized Chrysler plate continued to adorn the front end).
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The individual models were renamed to be in line with the newly launched Simca 1307/1308 series.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] While the first two digits in this model naming system stood for the base engine's displacement (1.6 L in the case of the Chrysler 160), the latter two represented the French fiscal class in which the car slotted.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] However, in the UK, where only the 180 versions were marketed, it retained its name.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] To add to the confusion, the 2.0-litre retained its name in all markets.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] In 1979, the large Chrysler saw the sale of its parent company, Chrysler Europe, to the French PSA concern, due to Chrysler's financial difficulties.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Some minor reshuffles in the range were made.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] A minor change of the exterior decals also occurred.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The range was sold for only one year with the new names, as for 1981 PSA presented a replacement, the brand-new Talbot Tagora.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Peugeot had originally intended to replace it with the Solara, the saloon version of the Alpine, which was launched in April 1980.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The production of petrol-engine Talbot 1610 stopped at the Barreiros plant, but diesel versions continued under the Talbot badge until 1982 for the Spanish market.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The Chrysler 180/2-litre found its best market in Spain after production had been transferred there in the later 1970s.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The marketplace was different in France and the UK.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Its mixed pedigree and non-established brand did not fit in well with the expectations of more nationalistic buyers and reviewers.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] There was little that would make the car stand out among the crowd of similar cars, many of which already had an established position in the class.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] By 1976, with the number of cars sold in the UK not yet up to 10,000, British sales had settled down at the annual rate of about 2,000 which was seen to be below the company's expectations, but UK sales were greater than those in France.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] In France, the sales of the Chrysler were so disappointing that the old Simca 1501 was offered again for 1974 (it had been kept in production after Chrysler's launch, mainly for export markets, to use up the remaining parts).
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] In the British market the car's chances against rivals, such as the successful Rover SD1, were also hampered by the lack of engines larger than the 2.0 L, as the competitors offered six- or even eight-cylinder units, as they were not restricted by the French tax regulations.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Moreover, Chrysler seemed not to support the model after its launch.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Advertising was limited and updates scarce and insignificant.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] Chrysler did not make available an upmarket model with features as power windows or central locking, even though they were all available in the smaller Simca 1307, launched around the time when the 180 was in mid-cycle.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] A variant of the Chrysler 180 was produced in Australia from 1975 to 1978 by Chrysler Australia as the Chrysler Centura.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] The Centura was offered with a choice of 4-cylinder and 6-cylinder engines mated to a manual or automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-180] It was fitted with a larger nose and modified front radiator grille to accommodate the larger straight-six engine and allow more airflow to the radiator; four round headlamps completed the makeover.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The brand has been historically popular.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] However starting in the late 2010s, the brand has been overshadowed by other brands owned by Stellantis.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] As of model year 2026, the company's production vehicle lineup solely consists of the Pacifica and Voyager minivans, although there are currently plans by Stellantis to revive the brand, as seen with the Chrysler Airflow concept, due to its heritage and continued popularity.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The first Chrysler cars were introduced on January 5, 1924, at the New York Automobile Show – one year before Chrysler Corporation itself was created.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] These cars, launched by Maxwell Motors, had a new high-compression six-cylinder, a seven-bearing crankshaft, carburetor air cleaner, replaceable oil filter, and four-wheel hydraulic brakes.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Features like this had never been offered in a medium-priced car before, and the 32,000 first-year record sales proved the popularity of this model.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1926, Chrysler introduced the Chrysler 70, named for its ability to hit 70 mph.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1927, Chrysler had four models: the Chrysler 50, 60, 70, and Imperial 80.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Chrysler was in fourth place in sales, with 192,082 units delivered.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1928, Chrysler invested $23 million to expand its plants.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1930, Chrysler began wiring the Chrysler Model 70 and 77 for radios.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Chrysler also became the first car to offer the downdraft carburetor on its models.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] With the new carburetor, Chrysler also received a new cam-driven fuel pump.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] For the 1931 model, Chrysler received new radiator grilles, a new Chrysler Spitfire engine, and automatic spark control.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The 1932 Chryslers introduced the Floating Power rubber engine mounts, which eliminated further vibrations from the chassis.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] A vacuum-controlled automatic clutch, Oilite bearings, and the first universal joints with roller bearings were also added.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1933, Chrysler models received a host of new improvements, including a new three-speed manual transmission that used helical gears – for silent use.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Chrysler engines received new alloy valve seats for better reliability, along with new spring shackles, which improved lubrication.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1934, the Chrysler 6 introduced an independent front coil spring suspension and received vent windows that rolled down with the side glass.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Chrysler also introduced its revolutionary Chrysler Airflow, which included a welded Unibody, a wind-tunnel-designed aerodynamic body for a better power-to-power ratio and better handling.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1935, Chrysler introduced the Plymouth-based Chrysler Airstream Six, which gave customers an economical modern alternative to the radically styled Airflows.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Airflow received an updated front hood and grille in 1935.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] For 1936, the Chrysler Airflow received an enlarged luggage compartment, a new roof, and a new adjustable front seat.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Airstream Six and Eight of the previous year were renamed the Chrysler Six and Deluxe Eight.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Automatic overdrive was optional for both cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] For 1937, the Airflow cars were mostly discontinued, besides the C-17 Airflow, which received a final facelift.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Only 4600 C-17 Airflows were built in 1937.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Chrysler Six and Chrysler Eight were respectively renamed the Royal and Imperial and gained isolated rubber body mounts to remove road vibrations.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1938, the Chrysler Royal received the new 95 HP Gold Seal Inline 6.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1939, Chrysler unveiled *Superfinish* a process in which all major chassis components subject to wear were finished to a mirror-like surface.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Other features new to Chrysler were push-button door locks, and rotary-type door latches.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1940, Chrysler introduced sealed beam headlights on its cars, which in turn improved night visibility by 50%.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Mid-year, in 1940, Chrysler introduced the Highlander as a special edition featuring popular features and a Scottish plaid interior.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The luxury sport model, called the Saratoga, was also added to the New Yorker range as the Imperial became the exclusive limousine model.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1941, Chrysler introduced the Fluid Drive semi-automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] 1942 Chryslers were redesigned with a wrap-a-round chrome grille and concealed running boards for this abbreviated model year; civilian production stopped by February 1942.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1946, Chrysler redesigned the 1942 cars and reintroduced the Town & Country.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1949, Chrysler came out with the first all-new redesign in almost a decade.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1949, Chrysler moved the ignition to key only instead of having a key and push-button.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] They also reintroduced the nine-passenger station wagon body style to the line.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] For 1950, Chrysler updated the overly conservative 1949 models by lowering cars slightly, updating the grille to appear more simple, replacing the chrome fin tail lamps with flush units, and removing the third brake light from the trunk lid.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Also in 1950, Chrysler introduced disc brakes on the Imperial, the new Chrysler Newport hardtop, power windows, and the padded safety dash.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Chrysler introduced their first overhead-valve, high-compression V8 engine in 1951; displacing 331 cubic inches, it was rated at 180 bhp, 20 more horsepower than the new-for-1949 Cadillac V8.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] It was unique as the only American V8 engine designed with hemispherical combustion chambers.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] After successfully winning Mexican Road Races, the engine was upgraded to 250 bhp by 1955.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Although Chrysler did not build a small sporty car (such as the Chevrolet Corvette and the Ford Thunderbird), they decided to build a unique sporting car based on the New Yorker hardtop coupe that featured a 300-bhp "Hemi" V8.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] To add to the car's uniqueness, the car was given a grille from the Imperial and side trim from the less-adorned Windsor.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] A PowerFlite 2-speed automatic transmission was the only available gearbox.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] It was marketed as the Chrysler 300, emphasizing the engine's horsepower, continuing a luxury sport approach introduced earlier with the Chrysler Saratoga.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1955, the flagship Imperial was spun off into its own line of luxury cars, slotted above Chrysler, Imperial would remain a separate brand through 1975, and would be reintroduced in 1980, offering a single model through 1983.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Imperial returned as the flagship Chrysler for model years 1990-1993.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] A 1955 restyle by newly hired Virgil Exner saw a dramatic rise in Chrysler sales, which rose even more in 1957 when the entire line was dramatically restyled a second time with a sloping front end and high-flying tailfins at the rear.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Although well received at first, it soon became apparent that quality control was compromised to get the new cars to market on an accelerated schedule.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1957, all Chrysler products were installed with Torsion-Aire front suspension, which was a Torsion bar suspension only for the front wheels that followed two years after Packard installed Torsion-Level suspension on both the front and rear wheels.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Sales of all Chrysler models plummeted in 1958 and 1959 despite improvements in quality.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Throughout the mid-and late-1950s, Chryslers were available in top-line New Yorker, mid-line Saratoga, and base Windsor series.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Exner's designs for the Chrysler brand in the early 1960s were overblown versions of the late 1950s, which were unhelpful in sales.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Exner left his post by 1962, leaving Elwood Engel, a recent transfer from Ford Motor Co, in charge of Chrysler styling.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Although early 1960s Chrysler cars reflected Virgil Exner's exaggerated styling, Elwood Engel's influence was evident as early as 1963, when a restyled, trimmer, boxier Chrysler was introduced.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Desoto lines, along with the Windsor and Saratoga series, were replaced with the Newport, while New Yorker continued as the luxury model, while Imperial continued to be the top-of-the-line brand.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Chrysler 300, officially part of the New Yorker product line, continued in production as a high-performance coupe through 1965, adding a different letter of the alphabet for each year of production, starting with the 300-B of 1956, through the 300-L of 1965.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] 1962 saw a "non-letter" 300, which was lower in price but was equipped with downgraded standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The 1965 Chryslers were again dramatically restyled, with a thoroughly modern unit body and larger engines up to 413 cubic inches.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] They were squared off and slab-sided, with optional glass-covered headlamps that retracted when the headlights were turned on and a swept-back roofline for 2-door hardtop models.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1963, Bob Hope was a spokesperson of *The Chrysler Theatre*, an anthology series sponsored by the brand.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The same year the Chrysler Turbine Car was introduced.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] It was an experimental two-door hardtop coupe powered by a turbine engine and manufactured from 1963 to 1964.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Italian design studio Carrozzeria Ghia constructed the bodywork, and Chrysler completed the final assembly in Detroit.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] A total of 55 Turbine Cars were manufactured.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Cordoba was introduced by Chrysler for the 1975 model year as an upscale personal luxury car that replaced the 300, competing with the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Buick Regal, and Mercury Cougar.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Cordoba was originally intended to be a Plymouth—the names Mirada, Premier, Sebring, and Grand Era were associated with the project; all except Grand Era would be used on later Chrysler, Dodge, and Eagle vehicles, though only the Dodge Mirada would be related to the Cordoba.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] However, losses from the newly introduced full-size C-body models due to the 1973 oil crisis, along with the investment in the Turbine Car that did not produce a product to sell, encouraged Chrysler executives to seek higher profits by marketing the model under the more upscale Chrysler brand.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The car was a success, with over 150,000 examples sold in 1975, a sales year that was otherwise dismal for the company.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] For the 1976 model year, sales increased slightly to 165,000.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The mildly revised 1977 version also sold well, with just under 140,000 cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The success of using the Chrysler nameplate strategy is contrasted to sales of its similar and somewhat cheaper corporate cousin, the Dodge Charger SE.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Interiors were more luxurious than the Dodge Charger SE and much more than the top-line standard intermediates (Plymouth Fury, Dodge Coronet) with a velour cloth notchback bench seat and folding armrest standard.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Optionally available were bucket seats upholstered in Corinthian leather with a center armrest and cushion or, at extra cost, a center console with floor shifter and storage compartment.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1977, Chrysler brought out a new mid-size line of cars called LeBaron (a name previously used for an Imperial model), which included a coupe, sedan, and station wagon.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1982, the LeBaron moved to the front-wheel drive Chrysler K platform, where it was the upscale brand's lowest-priced offering.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] It was initially available in just sedan and coupe versions.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In early 1982, it was released in a convertible version, bringing to the market the first factory-built open-topped domestic vehicle since the 1976 Cadillac Eldorado.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] A station wagon version called the **Town and Country** was added as well.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] A special Town and Country convertible was also made from 1983 until 1986 in limited quantities (1,105 total), which, like the wagon, featured simulated wood paneling that made it resemble the original 1940s Town and Country.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] This model was part of the well-equipped Mark Cross option package for the latter years.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1982, the R-body line was discontinued, and the New Yorker nameplate transferred to the smaller M-body line.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Up to this point, the Chrysler M-body entry had been sold as LeBaron, but that name was moved to a new K-car-based FWD line (refer to the Chrysler LeBaron article for information on the 1977–81 M-bodies).
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Following the nameplate swap, the M-body line was consolidated and simplified.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] 360 V8 engines were gone, as were coupes and station wagons (the K-car LeBaron's coupe and wagon replaced them).
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Fifth Avenue option was still available as a $1,244 option package.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] It was adapted from the earlier LeBaron's package, with a distinctive vinyl roof, electroluminescent opera lamps, and a rear fascia adapted from the Dodge Diplomat.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Interiors featured button-tufted, pillow-soft seats covered in either "Kimberley velvet" or "Corinthian leather," choices that would continue unchanged throughout the car's run.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In addition, the carpet was thicker than that offered in the base New Yorker, Diplomat and Gran Fury/Caravelle Salon, and the interior had more chrome trim.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The last year for Chrysler's Cordoba coupe was 1983.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] That year, Chrysler introduced a new front-wheel-drive New Yorker model based on a stretched K-Car platform.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Additionally, a less expensive, less equipped version of the new New Yorker was sold as the Chrysler E-Class in 1983 and 1984.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] More upscale stretched K-Car models were also sold as Chrysler Executive sedans and limousines.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] With the 1984 model year, the New Yorker Fifth Avenue was now simply called Fifth Avenue, setting the name that would continue for six successful years.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Fifth Avenue production was moved from Windsor, Ontario to St.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Beginning in late 1986 through the 1989 model year, they were manufactured at the American Motors plant in Kenosha, Wisconsin (purchased by Chrysler in 1987).
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Fifth Avenue also far outsold its Dodge Diplomat and Plymouth Gran Fury siblings, with a much greater proportion of sales going to private customers despite its higher price tag.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Production peaked at 118,000 cars for 1986, and the Fifth Avenue stood out in a by-now K-car-dominated lineup as Chrysler's lone concession to traditional RWD American sedans.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Chrysler introduced a new mid-size four-door hatchback model in 1985 under the LeBaron GTS nameplate.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] It was sold alongside the mid-size LeBaron sedan, coupe, convertible, and station wagon.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The LeBaron coupe and convertible were redesigned in 1987.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Unlike previous LeBarons, this new coupe and convertible had unique styling instead of being just two-door versions of the sedan.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The new design featured hidden headlamps (through 1992) and full-width taillights.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The New Yorker was redesigned for the 1988 model year and now included a standard V6 engine.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] This generation of New Yorker also saw the return of hidden headlamps, which had not been available on the New Yorker since the 1981 R-body version.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1989, Chrysler brought out the TC by Maserati luxury roadster as a more affordable alternative to Cadillac's Allante.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] It was a joint venture model between Chrysler and Maserati.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] 1990 saw the previous relationship between New Yorker and Fifth Avenue return, as Fifth Avenue became a model of the New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] There was some substantive difference, however, as the New Yorker Fifth Avenue used a slightly longer chassis than the standard car.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The new New Yorker Fifth Avenue's larger interior volume classified it as a full-size model this time despite having smaller exterior dimensions than the first generation.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] For 1990, Chrysler's new 3.3L V6 engine was the standard and only choice, teamed with the company's A-604 four-speed electronic automatic transaxle.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Beginning in 1991, a larger 3.8L V6 became optional.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] It delivered the same 147 horsepower as the 3.3 but had more torque.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The New Yorker Fifth Avenue's famous seats, long noted for their button-tufted appearance and sofa-like comfort, continued to be offered with the customer's choice of velour or leather, with the former "Corinthian leather" replaced by that of the Mark Cross company.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Leather-equipped cars bore the Mark Cross logo on the seats and, externally, on an emblem attached to the brushed aluminum band ahead of the rear door opera windows.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The early 1990s saw a revival of the Imperial as a high-end sedan in Chrysler's lineup.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Unlike the 1955 through 1983 Imperial, this car was a model of Chrysler, not its own marque.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Based on the Y platform, it represented the top full-size model in Chrysler's lineup; below it was the similar New Yorker Fifth Avenue, and below that was the shorter wheelbase New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The reintroduction of the Imperial was two years after the Lincoln Continental was changed to a front-wheel-drive sedan with a V6 engine.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Other domestic competitors in this segment included the Cadillac Sedan de Ville/Fleetwood, Oldsmobile 98, and Buick Electra/Park Avenue.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Though closely related, the Imperial differed from the New Yorker Fifth Avenue in many ways.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Imperial's nose was more wedge-shaped, while the New Yorker Fifth Avenue's had a sharper, more angular profile (the New Yorker Fifth Avenue was later restyled with a more rounded front end).
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The rears of the two cars also differed.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Like the front, the New Yorker Fifth Avenue's rear came to stiffer angles, while the Imperial's rear end came to more rounded edges.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Also found on the Imperial were full-width taillights, which were similar to those of the Chrysler TC, as well as the early 1980s Imperial coupe, while the New Yorker Fifth Avenue came with smaller vertical taillights.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Initially, the 1990 Imperial was powered by the 147 hp (110 kW) 3.3L *EGA* V6 engine, which was rated at 185 lb⋅ft (251 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] For 1991, the 3.3L V6 was replaced by the larger 3.8L *EGH* V6.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Although horsepower only increased to 150 hp (112 kW), with the new larger 3.8L V6 torque increased to 215 lb⋅ft (292 N⋅m) at 2750 rpm.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] A four-speed automatic transmission was standard with both engines.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Also new for 1990 was a redesigned LeBaron sedan, which offered a standard V6 engine.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Later models would also be available with 4-cylinder engines.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Town & Country minivan was restyled for 1991 in conjunction with the restyling of the Dodge and Plymouth minivan models.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] 1991 would also be the last year for the TC by Maserati, leaving the LeBaron as the brand's sole coupe and convertible options.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The first generation of the Chrysler Concorde debuted at the 1992 North American International Auto Show in Detroit as a 1993 model.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] It debuted as a single, well-equipped model with a base price of US$18,341.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Out of all the LH sedans, the first generation Concorde was most closely related to the Eagle Vision.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Concorde was given a more traditional image than the Vision.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The two shared nearly all sheet metal in common, with the main differences limited to their grilles, rear fascias, bodyside moldings, and wheel choices.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Concorde featured a modern take on Chrysler's signature waterfall grille.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] It was split into six sections divided by body-colored strips with the Chrysler Pentastar logo on the center strip.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Concorde's rear fascia was highlighted by a full-width and full-height lightbar between the taillights, giving the appearance that the taillights stretched across the entire trunk.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In keeping with its upscale position, Concorde's body side moldings incorporated bright chrome (later golden-colored) work not found on its Dodge or Eagle siblings.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] On Concordes with gray lower body paint color, the gray came up to the chrome beltline; on Visions, the gray lower body paint area was smaller and much more subtle.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Wheel styles, which included available aluminum wheels with a Spiralcast design, were also unique to the Chrysler LH sedans (Concorde, LHS, New Yorker); Dodge and Eagle had different wheel styles.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Introduced in May 1993 for the 1994 model year, the Chrysler LHS was the top-of-the-line model for the division, as well as the most expensive of the Chrysler LH platform cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] All the LH-series models shared a 113.0-inch (2,870 mm) wheelbase and were developed using Chrysler's new computer drafting system.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The car was differentiated from the division's New Yorker sedan by its bucket leather seats (the New Yorker had a bench seat) and standard features such as alloy wheels that were options on the New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Further differences between the Chrysler LHS and its New Yorker counterpart were a floor console and shifter, five-passenger seating, lack of chrome trim, an upgraded interior, and a sportier image.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The New Yorker was dropped after the 1996 model year in favor of a six-passenger option on the LHS.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The LHS received a minor face change in 1995 when the corporate-wide Pentastar emblem was replaced with the revived Chrysler brand emblem.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Unlike the New Yorker, leather seats were standard.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The New Yorker came standard with the 3.5L *EGE* which produced 214 hp (160 kW).
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Chrysler gave the New Yorker a more "traditional American" luxury image and the LHS a more European performance image (as was done with the Eagle Vision).
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Little separated New Yorker from LHS in appearance, with New Yorker's chrome hood trim, body-color cladding, standard chrome wheel covers, 15-inch wheels, column shifter, and front bench seat being the only noticeable differences.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] An option is provided for 16-inch wheels and a firmer suspension type ("touring suspension").
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] This option eliminated the technical differences between New Yorker and LHS.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] LHS came with almost all of New Yorker's optional features as standard equipment and featured the firmer tuned suspension to go with its more European image.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] During the 1994 model run, various changes were made to the New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] On the outside, New Yorker was switched to new accent-color body cladding, whereas LHS received body-color cladding.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] This change aligned the New Yorker with the Chrysler Concorde, which also had accent-color cladding.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Instead of standard 15-inch and optional 16-inch wheels, the 16-inch wheels became standard, and the 15-inch versions were dropped.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Likewise, the touring suspension option available on early 1994 New Yorker models was discontinued, leaving only "ride-tuned" suspension.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1995, the Chrysler Sebring was introduced as a coupe, replacing the LeBaron coupe, and the new JA platform Chrysler Cirrus replaced the outgoing LeBaron sedan.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] A year later, a convertible version of the Sebring went on the market and replaced the LeBaron convertible.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 1999, Chrysler introduced the new LH platform 300M sedan alongside a redesigned LHS.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The 300M was originally designed to be the next-generation Eagle Vision, but since the Eagle brand had been discontinued in 1998, it instead became a Chrysler sedan.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 2000, the Voyager and Grand Voyager minivans were repositioned as Chrysler models due to the phasing out of the Plymouth brand.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 2001, a sedan was added to the Sebring model line and served as a replacement for the discontinued Cirrus.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] That same year, the Chrysler brand added a retro-styled PT Cruiser as well as the Prowler roadster which had previously been a Plymouth model.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] By 2004, all Chrysler brand minivans were now sold under the Town & Country nameplate.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The 2000s also saw the Chrysler brand move into the fast-growing crossover/SUV segment with the introduction of the Chrysler Pacifica crossover in 2004 and the Chrysler Aspen SUV in 2007.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The Pacifica would be discontinued in 2008 (the nameplate would return on a new minivan model in 2017), and the Aspen would be discontinued in 2009.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Between 2004 and 2008, Chrysler offered a two-seat coupe and convertible model called Crossfire.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] This was in addition to Chrysler's five-seat Sebring coupe (through 2005) and four-seat convertible being sold at the time.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 2005, Chrysler introduced the LX platform Chrysler 300 sedan, which replaced both the 300M and Concorde.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] It was the brand's first rear-wheel-drive sedan since the discontinuation of the Chrysler Fifth Avenue in 1989.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] It was also the first time a Chrysler sedan was available with a V8 engine since 1989.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Chrysler Corporation began working with Italian automaker Fiat, culminating with the 2014 merger of the two companies.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The newly formed Fiat Chrysler Automobiles (FCA) set a long-term goal of reviving the Chrysler brand as a full luxury brand to compete again with Cadillac and other luxury brands, partly by rebadging automobiles from other brands in the group.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] However, none of these plans ultimately came to fruition in the decade.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In 2011, the brand's winged emblem was modified, eliminating the historic blue ribbon center which dated from the 1930s, replacing it with a blue-backed "Chrysler" nameplate.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Also that year, the Chrysler 300 was restyled, and the Sebring was rebranded as the Chrysler 200.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In May 2014, FCA announced it would make the brand a mainstream brand with premium features.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] A redesigned Chrysler 200 was introduced for 2015 but would be discontinued in 2017 as FCA shifted focus more towards SUVs and minivans.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] For 2017, the Chrysler Pacifica nameplate returned on a new minivan, replacing the long-running Town & Country, Voyager, and Grand Voyager.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] During this time, Chrysler's quality and customer satisfaction ratings had been below average, according to Consumer Reports and J.D.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Chrysler did have a few quality successes during this period.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Strategic Vision named Chrysler an overall winner in 2015 for strong customer appeal, and with the rise in quality of all cars, the difference between high and low "problem-counting" ratings is relatively small.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In the early 2020s, Chrysler was facing an uncertain future with just two vehicle models in its lineup: the Chrysler Pacifica minivan and the Chrysler 300 sedan, which was last redesigned in 2010.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In March 2023, Stellantis CEO Carlos Tavares said the brand would be "relaunched" with new models.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] One of those models is expected to be an electric crossover SUV by 2025, previewed by the Chrysler Airflow concept.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] In December 2023, the Chrysler 300 was discontinued.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Furthermore, the company says it plans to make the Chrysler brand fully electric by 2028.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] Chrysler's product lineup in North America by 2030 will include the Pacifica, Airflow, Arrow, and Arrow Cross.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-brand] The brand's current lineup consists of the Chrysler Pacifica minivan and its sister vehicle the Chrysler Voyager.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The **Chrysler Centura** is a mid-size car which was produced by Chrysler Australia between 1975 and 1978.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] It was based on Chrysler Europe's Chrysler 180 model, but was also available with larger Australian-made Hemi Six engines.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] It also meant fewer changes were needed to "Australianise" the car, making it economical to assemble.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Additional, largely cosmetic changes included a new grill, headlights, bonnet and rear panel and taillights.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] A brake proportioning valve was fitted to all Centuras from factory to compensate for weight transfer during braking.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] When the car "nose-dived" under heavy braking, a mechanical link connected to the proportioning valve reduced the brake pressure on the rear wheels, to prevent them from locking up and causing the back of the car to slide around.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] This was typical of many European cars of the time but uncommon in Australian cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Chrysler also experimented with fitting a 5.2-litre (318 ci) American-made V8 but decided that the body lacked the rigidity to cope with the larger engine; the V8 version never went into production.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The KB Centuras sold and assembled in Australia not only had a 1981 cc version of the four-cylinder Simca engine but were also available with Australian-made 6-cylinder pushrod 3523/4014 cc hemi engines and BorgWarner 3-speed automatic and 3- or 4-speed manual gearboxes.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The four offered 122 hp (SAE), the sixes 142/167 hp (SAE) respectively.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The KB series was sold in XL and GL trims, the latter having more equipment as standard.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] All KB Centuras had a tachometer and a clock, low fuel light (rare for 1975), rear bumper overriders, console (no storage) and optional vinyl roofs.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] There were no rear demister fitted, although a Smiths unit was fitted by some dealers.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The KB model's European pedigree was obvious, with instrumentation in the opposite order and steering column controls on opposite sides.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The sixes also came with larger brakes (279 mm (11.0 in) ventilated front discs and 228.6 mm (9.0 in) rear finned drums) and a tandem brake reservoir.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The six-cylinder Hemi cars used a 5-stud wheel bolt pattern, and the early four-cylinder cars used a 4-stud wheel bolt pattern and only featured solid unventilated brake discs.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Later four-cylinder cars shared the same brakes and stud pattern as the sixes, and thus the same wheels.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] All Centura models were factory fitted with rack-and-pinion steering, however there was no power steering option.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Steering could be extremely heavy, so correct tyre fitment and pressures were a must.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Factory / dealer fitted air, with the unit located below the heater controls was available but seldom optioned.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] No Centura models were fitted with starter motor relays, which instead put the cranking load onto the ignition switch internal terminals when cranking, which reduced the ignition switch life in some cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Traction in wet weather proved to be poor, with some cars only having an open differential, relatively large six-cylinder Hemi engine and very light weight over the rear wheels.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The importation of the bodies from France into Australia was complicated in 1973 by industrial action, with dockside unions protesting against French Pacific island nuclear testing.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] There was a myth that many early KB bodies spent months on wharfs exposed to salt air, creating corrosion problems later in these cars' lives.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The main problem this caused was to delay the car's initial release onto the market.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Centuras overall are generally not very rust-prone compared to contemporary vehicles of the time, however rust tends to occur in the usual places where moisture and mud tend to accumulate.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Areas to check are below the windscreen on both sides of the car, the firewall where the heater is mounted, and the lower sills, especially behind the back wheels and below the front doors.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The vinyl roof cover which was a popular and standard fitment on GL models (delete option only) was also a source of water entrapment, creating the possibility of rust in the "A" pillars and gutters.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] KC models were more prone to rusting than KB models.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] This can be attributed to the KC panels being made in Australia from different steel than the KB's imported panels.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] In addition to the union bans on French imports, parts supply and local Chrysler support for used vehicles also became more complicated when in 1978, Chrysler Europe went bankrupt and was taken over by Peugeot.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] This Peugeot takeover was soon followed by several French Peugeot/Talbot factory strikes worsening the problems in sourcing parts in Australia.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The mix of metric and imperial fasteners used on the 6-cylinder cars is not anything unusual as many contemporary cars such as Holden Commodores had the same mix.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The combination of overseas and Australian parts can make them challenging vehicles to maintain, however most wearing components are readily available from spare-parts suppliers.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] From the early 1980s parts became difficult to source, with existing stocks being used up and with the wait for French parts sometimes a long one.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] In the early 1990s Mitsubishi ceased supporting these vehicles with spare parts.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Existing stocks of spare parts were auctioned off, and all stock which wasn't sold was unfortunately disposed of.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Six-cylinder cars sold four-to-one in the Australian market over the four-cylinder cars.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] They had a reputation for providing reasonably decent handling, outstanding torque and outstanding acceleration.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Sports options available on Centura models included dealer-fitted stenciled sports stripes (bonnet and sides), special 'Boca-Raton' striped cloth seats and styled steel or alloy wheels.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Most of the interior and exterior dealer options from the larger Valiant models were applicable to the Centura, from the dealership.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The Centura's main competitors in Australia were four- and six-cylinder Australian-made versions of the Ford Cortina and General Motors' LH, LX and UC Holden Torana and Sunbird.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The Centura had much more interior room and boot space than these main rivals, along with a far more violent power-to-weight ratio.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Centuras were also seen to compete to a lesser extent with larger-bodied Australian Holdens, Chrysler Valiants (including the sporting Charger coupe) and Ford Falcons.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Most competitors, although often lacking the outright fierce acceleration of the six-cylinder Centura, proved less rust-prone and generally had more modern styling.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] In retrospect the rather compact Centura was not a typical 1970s medium-sized car.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] It wouldn't be until after the cancellation of the Centura, when Holden released the Commodore in October 1978, for the market to have a vehicle with similar internal dimensions to the Centura.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Chrysler Australia was being starved of funds by its troubled American parent at this time, leaving the larger Valiant sedans persisting with the same chassis platform and basic body shape and interior (Valiants did not have face-level flow-through vents, unlike those in the Centura) for many years.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] This created an old-fashioned image of the Australian Chrysler-Valiant brand that may have also adversely impacted Centura sales.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The Chrysler 180 design was also rather dated by the time the cars arrived in the Australian market (later than intended), further adding to the old-fashioned image of the brand.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The bigger Valiants were still popular with rural Australians, who seemed to prefer larger cars, but the Centura didn't have the size or perceived style to meet the needs of that market, either.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The KC model (from June 1977 to the end of 1978) series dropped the 2.0 and 3.5 engines, but retained the larger 4.0-litre Hemi.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The 4.0-litre comprised a low-compression (7.6:1) Hemi engine which ran on standard-grade fuel and aided fuel economy, and a high-compression two-barrel (9.0:1) version of the Hemi for greater performance and towing ability.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The KC also featured greater Australian content, using VDO gauges (tachometer now an optional extra available only on Sports Pack KC, replacing the factory fitted KC clock), a Valiant-style steering wheel, steering column and various other parts from the larger Australian Valiant lineup.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The KC was offered in GL or luxury GLX trims, along with the addition of sports package options which could also be ordered.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] KC models could be differentiated by the use of capitalised and serifed block lettering typeface for the "Centura" badges (the KB had this in cursive) and a silver grille insert (KBs had a black grille with a silver border and highlights).
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] By 1979, the Centura had been replaced by the four-cylinder Chrysler Sigma, of Mitsubishi origins.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] Centuras are now very rare on Australian roads, although they appear slightly more common in South Australia.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] This is probably due to an enduring local loyalty to the Chrysler brand, as they had a manufacturing plant in that state before selling it to Mitsubishi in 1980.
[src:chrysler-centura/chrysler-centura] The nuclear ban's impact on production and parts supply, subsequent rust problems, extreme light weight over the rear of the car, comparatively violent acceleration and challenging handling were likely all factors that contributed to their relatively rapid disappearance from Australian roads.
